'''Rose position''' is a position in which a patient is placed while undergoing a [[tonsillectomy]],<ref name="SouzaAl.1995">{{cite book|author1=De Souza|author2=C. Et Al.|title=Textbook Of The Ear, Nose And Throat|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=th_DNkgjWR8C&pg=PA180|accessdate=16 August 2012|date=1 January 1995|publisher=Orient Blackswan|isbn=978-81-250-0275-8|pages=180}}</ref>[[adenoidectomy]] or [[uvulopalatopharyngoplasty]].<ref name="LeeToh2007">{{cite book|author1=K. J. Lee|author2=Elizabeth H. Toh|title=Otolaryngology: A Surgical Notebook|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=B-qwzxD2tpIC&pg=PA56|accessdate=16 August 2012|date=11 July 2007|publisher=Thieme|isbn=978-3-13-138351-8|pages=56}}</ref>

==Position==
In this position both the head and neck are extended. This is done by keeping a sand bag under the patient's shoulder blade. For a patient with a [[kyphosis]] or a stiff neck, raise the head piece of the table so that the head ring really does support the head.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.wikisurgery.com/index.php?title=Tonsillectomy#SECTION_3.00__POSITION |title=WikiSurgery - Information on Tonsillectomy |first=Chandra |last=Ramyad |work=wikisurgery.com |year=2010 [last update] |accessdate=16 August 2012}}</ref> Its contraindicated in patients with [[Down's syndrome]] owing to atlanto-axial instability.<ref name="VoelkelMacNee2002">{{cite book|author1=Norbert F. Voelkel|author2=William MacNee|title=Chronic Obstructive Lung Diseases|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=ox5N5Gru_QkC&pg=PA380|accessdate=16 August 2012|year=2002|publisher=PMPH-USA|isbn=978-1-55009-133-5|pages=380}}</ref>

==History==
This position owes its name to a staff nurse by name Rose who suggested this position to the surgeon. In fact it must be called as Sister Rose position.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.drtbalu.co.in/tonsillectomy.html |title=Tonsillectomy by Dr. T. Balu |first=T |last=Balu |work=drtbalu.co.in |year=2007 [last update]   |accessdate=16 August 2012}}</ref>

